first_page_comments_list.comment: I think probably the biggest red-flag phrase has got to be "This has changed my life!"  Like, unless that foundation is clearing your debt or getting you free childcare, it's not changing your life.

I think “makeup education” (for lack of a better term) plays a huge role in this. I had this one palette that was my ride or die palette, and it cost maybe $10 on sale. I used this thing non stop. I thought it was the best palette on the planet. Best formula, best everything. Then it broke and died, so I went searching for another one. During that quest, I found other brands and other palettes, and realized what I had been using was utter garbage. But I didn’t know that at the time! I was an ignorant happy clam with this horrific palette! I wonder if I was better off back then…it was much cheaper….but now I know what works for me and what doesn’t, and why, ect. So maybe it’s more of “makeup exposure “ than education, but I would have defended that garbage palette in comments (had I watched YouTube prior to the lock down) in videos with zero hesitation! My makeup knowledge was basically nonexistent.  I believe this to be part of the makeup view disconnect on many occasions.

Sorry for the long comment in advance!! I strongly dislike how she handled Lashgate but what pisses me off about her the most is she literally outed Cody’s ex for having a drug addiction which in turn sent her huge fanbase after this poor girl. I am a recovering addict with 4 years of sobriety so to me, what she did to that girl is so disgusting. She can talk about Cody all she wants in that regard if he allows it, that’s his business. I am always open about my addiction as well but I still wouldn’t want anyone talking about that online without my permission, especially someone so huge, and Mikayla clearly didn’t have it. I was disappointed to see that she told the entire internet about those struggles, especially when it seems like this girl was already having a hard time, but sending that many people to hate on her? It’s just cruel.

I could never support her anyway because I met someone who was personally bullied by her when they were in school. She cried when she told me how much it hurts her to see her bully all over social media. Its just sad to see how Mikayla acts. I would’ve loved to support a fellow New England girl who is making it in the beauty community, but she isn’t honest and clearly doesn’t care that she intentionally deceived her own fanbase. It could’ve already been over by now if she just said she put a lash on at the end and forgot to add a caption or tell everyone about it in the last clip! Like seriously! Oh well, it’s not like we can even see how anything looks on her skin with all the filters.

Anyway, I’m just tired of fake people. Dealt with enough in my life already so the last thing I want is to be wasting time on superficial influencers who value a dollar over the trust of their audience. Glad we have some of the good ones left, like you! Bc you don’t use these crazy filters, you are outspoken and upfront about any sponsorships, we know you don’t take just anything that comes your way either and you actually like the products you promote. So thank you for always being yourself and real with us.

I value and trust your opinions on makeup, even though there are things I won’t get because of personal preference or our different skin types. (for example, orange is the worst color on me but it looks perfect on you) for me I try to be thoughtful about what to buy and I would never be able to consider only one person’s review as the deciding factor of making that choice. You made some really good points. Glad you’re not afraid to speak out.
For foundation, i look at how long they think a "full day" is! An 8 hour wear test is kinda useless to me. I appreciate that you aim for 10-12 hours when you can!

You mentioned how different shadows (neutrals, blues, neons, etc) have different techniques and things you can and can't do with them. I would be interested in an overview video of different techniques you use for different kinds of shadows

My biggest red flag is when an influencer does a first impression on a bunch of products, finds one that they consider “life changing” and then never uses it again or maybe talks about it once six months after the the first impression video. A good review of a product for me is when the influencer tries a product as a first impression, says they really like it, and continues to use it in future videos (as an example). That lets me know that they truly enjoy the product. Now, does that make me want to buy the product? Not always, because I watch a bunch of different people with a variety of different skin types. I have dry skin and am prone to hormonal acne.

They found a Maybelline powder video that Makayla did recently where she never showed the actual application and acted as if it was the second coming of Jesus as she hid the sponsored statement or added it later. She lies about the false lashes and then didn't respond about it at all and she hid the sponsored statement and doubled down on her lies and made a joke out of her actions in subsequent videos. She has used filters too.  She has yet to apologize and she shouldn't be given the benefit of the doubt at all. That ship sailed.

The lash gate situation isn’t about her doing it. It is about the lack of accountability. A little mea culpa would go such a long way to fixing the situation.  This is a teachable moment for her, but she doesn’t seem to be learning.

My red flag is when they like EVERYTHING.   Every product can’t be life changing. Not all products are going to work for you but some people react to anything new like its the greatest thing they’ve ever tried. And the over the top excitement that doesn’t feel genuine.

A “red flag” that I learned yeeeears ago (been watching beauty videos since the beginning of time, lol), is when a beauty reviewer says “it’s the PEEEERRRRFECT nude lipstick!”. That doesn’t happen as much today, because people have become more educated on different skin tones and undertones, but 10-15 years ago, beauty enthusiasts on YouTube would recommend a nude lipstick shade as “universal”, calling it absolutely perfect for anyone, when obviously a nude depends on each individual’s unique coloring.

There are only a couple I trust now. We aren't stupid, when you watch long enough, you can see their tells and know when they are not into a product. Or when they are just don't something to help a brand. It's disgusting. I've really backed off the number of videos I watch because I just don't trust hardly anyone anymore. And yes, a first impression is a first impression, not a "review with swatches". Even if you do 3 looks in the video, if you're wiping them of to do another you aren't reviewing, you don't know how long it will wear, if it will cease, fade, etc. The smaller creators I used to love have gotten bigger and we're back to codes and links being pushed just like the bigger creators. I'm so disgusted with this community yet again. I watch you and like 3 other religiously, and then some others here and there, but I don't believe anything they say. The other thing that aggravates me is when their community tab has links to all releases, even if they haven't tried them or like them. It's all about the money for their links. If i wanted one long a$$ commercial, I'd watch TV. There's my rant for the day lol. 🤪

I’ll be 51 in 17 days and I personally can not thank you enough for this video! I don’t trust many, and honestly some creators are just amusing to me (not in a good way). I do trust you and that’s why I’m always here for it!
The problem with mikayla it’s that she didn’t even adress the problem, she is mocking the situation, and that it’s unacceptable. And the thing that other people have done worst it’s not an excuse.

The issue with Makayla is that she clearly put in the comments she was NOT wearing lashes as she was questioned. That’s just sad and awful.

It’s nice to find creators over 45 so thanks for the tag!
My biggest pet peeve’s is when a influencer call every other product a holy grail. 9 times out of 10 you’ll never see them use it again, and the misuse of the phrase life hanging. 💕
Yesssss I totally agree ❤sometimes hearing what people don’t like can be just as helpful as hearing what people do like!
Yes! Thank you for teaching me 3 years ago that I did not need to set my eye primer with a light shade. It was life changing :)

Yes! Yes! Yes! I always eye roll at the girls in their 20s saying it doesn’t crease or sink into their lines. I love your channel and Heather’s because of the age, skin type, climate, and style similarities. Plus you both have such honest reviews. If I see something new I have to check to see what Angie and Heather think first 😂

When things get really hyped up now, I feel like I wait and see what the general public says about. I fell for it too many times.

I’ve heard a few Youtubers talk about products that they want to try but they wouldn’t purchase and immediately turn around and ask the brand to send them it as PR. I’m always shocked after that when they actually send it to them. I understand the point of PR, but if you’re not willing to spend your own money on something then don’t turn around and tell us it’s worth spending our money on. It just makes me look at them differently.**
Sometimes I just watch people because I love their personalities. And then i forget that we don’t have the same preferences and then I buy everything they love oooopppssss 😂

ftBLiUO_hfw.title: Axiology Multisticks - Demo on Eyes Cheeks Lips Swatching #indiemakeup | PHYRRA
ftBLiUO_hfw.description:
Hello, beautiful creatures! Today's video is on the Axiology Multisticks. I demo these products for the first time, doing swatches on my eyes, cheeks and lips. I applaud Axiology for being plastic-free and using recycled trash as packaging, which can then be further recycled. I love seeing the push for recyclable or refillable packaging and wish more brands would embrace this.

Axiology multisticks are for people who like the no-makeup makeup look, for people who like monochromatic makeup, minimal makeup, or a slightly messy, grungy, imperfect undone look. 

I'm not personally a fan of no-makeup makeup or minimal makeup, but I know some of you are. I love bold and bright colors. I'm also not a fan of anything that doesn't set on my eyes. Because I have oily, hooded eyelids, if things don't set completely they crease and become a mess on me.

I'm bare faced in this video except for my skin care and my brows.

While these products are not to my personal taste, I can see buying these for friends who like minimal makeup to no makeup makeup. I would not purchase these for myself.

first_page_comments_list.comment: I think probably the biggest red-flag phrase has got to be "This has changed my life!"  Like, unless that foundation is clearing your debt or getting you free childcare, it's not changing your life.

I think “makeup education” (for lack of a better term) plays a huge role in this. I had this one palette that was my ride or die palette, and it cost maybe $10 on sale. I used this thing non stop. I thought it was the best palette on the planet. Best formula, best everything. Then it broke and died, so I went searching for another one. During that quest, I found other brands and other palettes, and realized what I had been using was utter garbage. But I didn’t know that at the time! I was an ignorant happy clam with this horrific palette! I wonder if I was better off back then…it was much cheaper….but now I know what works for me and what doesn’t, and why, ect. So maybe it’s more of “makeup exposure “ than education, but I would have defended that garbage palette in comments (had I watched YouTube prior to the lock down) in videos with zero hesitation! My makeup knowledge was basically nonexistent.  I believe this to be part of the makeup view disconnect on many occasions.

Sorry for the long comment in advance!! I strongly dislike how she handled Lashgate but what pisses me off about her the most is she literally outed Cody’s ex for having a drug addiction which in turn sent her huge fanbase after this poor girl. I am a recovering addict with 4 years of sobriety so to me, what she did to that girl is so disgusting. She can talk about Cody all she wants in that regard if he allows it, that’s his business. I am always open about my addiction as well but I still wouldn’t want anyone talking about that online without my permission, especially someone so huge, and Mikayla clearly didn’t have it. I was disappointed to see that she told the entire internet about those struggles, especially when it seems like this girl was already having a hard time, but sending that many people to hate on her? It’s just cruel.

I could never support her anyway because I met someone who was personally bullied by her when they were in school. She cried when she told me how much it hurts her to see her bully all over social media. Its just sad to see how Mikayla acts. I would’ve loved to support a fellow New England girl who is making it in the beauty community, but she isn’t honest and clearly doesn’t care that she intentionally deceived her own fanbase. It could’ve already been over by now if she just said she put a lash on at the end and forgot to add a caption or tell everyone about it in the last clip! Like seriously! Oh well, it’s not like we can even see how anything looks on her skin with all the filters.

Anyway, I’m just tired of fake people. Dealt with enough in my life already so the last thing I want is to be wasting time on superficial influencers who value a dollar over the trust of their audience. Glad we have some of the good ones left, like you! Bc you don’t use these crazy filters, you are outspoken and upfront about any sponsorships, we know you don’t take just anything that comes your way either and you actually like the products you promote. So thank you for always being yourself and real with us.

I value and trust your opinions on makeup, even though there are things I won’t get because of personal preference or our different skin types. (for example, orange is the worst color on me but it looks perfect on you) for me I try to be thoughtful about what to buy and I would never be able to consider only one person’s review as the deciding factor of making that choice. You made some really good points. Glad you’re not afraid to speak out.
For foundation, i look at how long they think a "full day" is! An 8 hour wear test is kinda useless to me. I appreciate that you aim for 10-12 hours when you can!

You mentioned how different shadows (neutrals, blues, neons, etc) have different techniques and things you can and can't do with them. I would be interested in an overview video of different techniques you use for different kinds of shadows

My biggest red flag is when an influencer does a first impression on a bunch of products, finds one that they consider “life changing” and then never uses it again or maybe talks about it once six months after the the first impression video. A good review of a product for me is when the influencer tries a product as a first impression, says they really like it, and continues to use it in future videos (as an example). That lets me know that they truly enjoy the product. Now, does that make me want to buy the product? Not always, because I watch a bunch of different people with a variety of different skin types. I have dry skin and am prone to hormonal acne.

They found a Maybelline powder video that Makayla did recently where she never showed the actual application and acted as if it was the second coming of Jesus as she hid the sponsored statement or added it later. She lies about the false lashes and then didn't respond about it at all and she hid the sponsored statement and doubled down on her lies and made a joke out of her actions in subsequent videos. She has used filters too.  She has yet to apologize and she shouldn't be given the benefit of the doubt at all. That ship sailed.

The lash gate situation isn’t about her doing it. It is about the lack of accountability. A little mea culpa would go such a long way to fixing the situation.  This is a teachable moment for her, but she doesn’t seem to be learning.

My red flag is when they like EVERYTHING.   Every product can’t be life changing. Not all products are going to work for you but some people react to anything new like its the greatest thing they’ve ever tried. And the over the top excitement that doesn’t feel genuine.

A “red flag” that I learned yeeeears ago (been watching beauty videos since the beginning of time, lol), is when a beauty reviewer says “it’s the PEEEERRRRFECT nude lipstick!”. That doesn’t happen as much today, because people have become more educated on different skin tones and undertones, but 10-15 years ago, beauty enthusiasts on YouTube would recommend a nude lipstick shade as “universal”, calling it absolutely perfect for anyone, when obviously a nude depends on each individual’s unique coloring.

There are only a couple I trust now. We aren't stupid, when you watch long enough, you can see their tells and know when they are not into a product. Or when they are just don't something to help a brand. It's disgusting. I've really backed off the number of videos I watch because I just don't trust hardly anyone anymore. And yes, a first impression is a first impression, not a "review with swatches". Even if you do 3 looks in the video, if you're wiping them of to do another you aren't reviewing, you don't know how long it will wear, if it will cease, fade, etc. The smaller creators I used to love have gotten bigger and we're back to codes and links being pushed just like the bigger creators. I'm so disgusted with this community yet again. I watch you and like 3 other religiously, and then some others here and there, but I don't believe anything they say. The other thing that aggravates me is when their community tab has links to all releases, even if they haven't tried them or like them. It's all about the money for their links. If i wanted one long a$$ commercial, I'd watch TV. There's my rant for the day lol. 🤪

I’ll be 51 in 17 days and I personally can not thank you enough for this video! I don’t trust many, and honestly some creators are just amusing to me (not in a good way). I do trust you and that’s why I’m always here for it!
The problem with mikayla it’s that she didn’t even adress the problem, she is mocking the situation, and that it’s unacceptable. And the thing that other people have done worst it’s not an excuse.

The issue with Makayla is that she clearly put in the comments she was NOT wearing lashes as she was questioned. That’s just sad and awful.

It’s nice to find creators over 45 so thanks for the tag!
My biggest pet peeve’s is when a influencer call every other product a holy grail. 9 times out of 10 you’ll never see them use it again, and the misuse of the phrase life hanging. 💕
Yesssss I totally agree ❤sometimes hearing what people don’t like can be just as helpful as hearing what people do like!
Yes! Thank you for teaching me 3 years ago that I did not need to set my eye primer with a light shade. It was life changing :)

Yes! Yes! Yes! I always eye roll at the girls in their 20s saying it doesn’t crease or sink into their lines. I love your channel and Heather’s because of the age, skin type, climate, and style similarities. Plus you both have such honest reviews. If I see something new I have to check to see what Angie and Heather think first 😂

When things get really hyped up now, I feel like I wait and see what the general public says about. I fell for it too many times.

I’ve heard a few Youtubers talk about products that they want to try but they wouldn’t purchase and immediately turn around and ask the brand to send them it as PR. I’m always shocked after that when they actually send it to them. I understand the point of PR, but if you’re not willing to spend your own money on something then don’t turn around and tell us it’s worth spending our money on. It just makes me look at them differently.**
Sometimes I just watch people because I love their personalities. And then i forget that we don’t have the same preferences and then I buy everything they love oooopppssss 😂

first_page_comments_list.comment: I think probably the biggest red-flag phrase has got to be "This has changed my life!"  Like, unless that foundation is clearing your debt or getting you free childcare, it's not changing your life.

I think “makeup education” (for lack of a better term) plays a huge role in this. I had this one palette that was my ride or die palette, and it cost maybe $10 on sale. I used this thing non stop. I thought it was the best palette on the planet. Best formula, best everything. Then it broke and died, so I went searching for another one. During that quest, I found other brands and other palettes, and realized what I had been using was utter garbage. But I didn’t know that at the time! I was an ignorant happy clam with this horrific palette! I wonder if I was better off back then…it was much cheaper….but now I know what works for me and what doesn’t, and why, ect. So maybe it’s more of “makeup exposure “ than education, but I would have defended that garbage palette in comments (had I watched YouTube prior to the lock down) in videos with zero hesitation! My makeup knowledge was basically nonexistent.  I believe this to be part of the makeup view disconnect on many occasions.

Sorry for the long comment in advance!! I strongly dislike how she handled Lashgate but what pisses me off about her the most is she literally outed Cody’s ex for having a drug addiction which in turn sent her huge fanbase after this poor girl. I am a recovering addict with 4 years of sobriety so to me, what she did to that girl is so disgusting. She can talk about Cody all she wants in that regard if he allows it, that’s his business. I am always open about my addiction as well but I still wouldn’t want anyone talking about that online without my permission, especially someone so huge, and Mikayla clearly didn’t have it. I was disappointed to see that she told the entire internet about those struggles, especially when it seems like this girl was already having a hard time, but sending that many people to hate on her? It’s just cruel.

I could never support her anyway because I met someone who was personally bullied by her when they were in school. She cried when she told me how much it hurts her to see her bully all over social media. Its just sad to see how Mikayla acts. I would’ve loved to support a fellow New England girl who is making it in the beauty community, but she isn’t honest and clearly doesn’t care that she intentionally deceived her own fanbase. It could’ve already been over by now if she just said she put a lash on at the end and forgot to add a caption or tell everyone about it in the last clip! Like seriously! Oh well, it’s not like we can even see how anything looks on her skin with all the filters.

Anyway, I’m just tired of fake people. Dealt with enough in my life already so the last thing I want is to be wasting time on superficial influencers who value a dollar over the trust of their audience. Glad we have some of the good ones left, like you! Bc you don’t use these crazy filters, you are outspoken and upfront about any sponsorships, we know you don’t take just anything that comes your way either and you actually like the products you promote. So thank you for always being yourself and real with us.

I value and trust your opinions on makeup, even though there are things I won’t get because of personal preference or our different skin types. (for example, orange is the worst color on me but it looks perfect on you) for me I try to be thoughtful about what to buy and I would never be able to consider only one person’s review as the deciding factor of making that choice. You made some really good points. Glad you’re not afraid to speak out.
For foundation, i look at how long they think a "full day" is! An 8 hour wear test is kinda useless to me. I appreciate that you aim for 10-12 hours when you can!

You mentioned how different shadows (neutrals, blues, neons, etc) have different techniques and things you can and can't do with them. I would be interested in an overview video of different techniques you use for different kinds of shadows

My biggest red flag is when an influencer does a first impression on a bunch of products, finds one that they consider “life changing” and then never uses it again or maybe talks about it once six months after the the first impression video. A good review of a product for me is when the influencer tries a product as a first impression, says they really like it, and continues to use it in future videos (as an example). That lets me know that they truly enjoy the product. Now, does that make me want to buy the product? Not always, because I watch a bunch of different people with a variety of different skin types. I have dry skin and am prone to hormonal acne.

They found a Maybelline powder video that Makayla did recently where she never showed the actual application and acted as if it was the second coming of Jesus as she hid the sponsored statement or added it later. She lies about the false lashes and then didn't respond about it at all and she hid the sponsored statement and doubled down on her lies and made a joke out of her actions in subsequent videos. She has used filters too.  She has yet to apologize and she shouldn't be given the benefit of the doubt at all. That ship sailed.

The lash gate situation isn’t about her doing it. It is about the lack of accountability. A little mea culpa would go such a long way to fixing the situation.  This is a teachable moment for her, but she doesn’t seem to be learning.

My red flag is when they like EVERYTHING.   Every product can’t be life changing. Not all products are going to work for you but some people react to anything new like its the greatest thing they’ve ever tried. And the over the top excitement that doesn’t feel genuine.

A “red flag” that I learned yeeeears ago (been watching beauty videos since the beginning of time, lol), is when a beauty reviewer says “it’s the PEEEERRRRFECT nude lipstick!”. That doesn’t happen as much today, because people have become more educated on different skin tones and undertones, but 10-15 years ago, beauty enthusiasts on YouTube would recommend a nude lipstick shade as “universal”, calling it absolutely perfect for anyone, when obviously a nude depends on each individual’s unique coloring.

There are only a couple I trust now. We aren't stupid, when you watch long enough, you can see their tells and know when they are not into a product. Or when they are just don't something to help a brand. It's disgusting. I've really backed off the number of videos I watch because I just don't trust hardly anyone anymore. And yes, a first impression is a first impression, not a "review with swatches". Even if you do 3 looks in the video, if you're wiping them of to do another you aren't reviewing, you don't know how long it will wear, if it will cease, fade, etc. The smaller creators I used to love have gotten bigger and we're back to codes and links being pushed just like the bigger creators. I'm so disgusted with this community yet again. I watch you and like 3 other religiously, and then some others here and there, but I don't believe anything they say. The other thing that aggravates me is when their community tab has links to all releases, even if they haven't tried them or like them. It's all about the money for their links. If i wanted one long a$$ commercial, I'd watch TV. There's my rant for the day lol. 🤪

I’ll be 51 in 17 days and I personally can not thank you enough for this video! I don’t trust many, and honestly some creators are just amusing to me (not in a good way). I do trust you and that’s why I’m always here for it!
The problem with mikayla it’s that she didn’t even adress the problem, she is mocking the situation, and that it’s unacceptable. And the thing that other people have done worst it’s not an excuse.

The issue with Makayla is that she clearly put in the comments she was NOT wearing lashes as she was questioned. That’s just sad and awful.

It’s nice to find creators over 45 so thanks for the tag!
My biggest pet peeve’s is when a influencer call every other product a holy grail. 9 times out of 10 you’ll never see them use it again, and the misuse of the phrase life hanging. 💕
Yesssss I totally agree ❤sometimes hearing what people don’t like can be just as helpful as hearing what people do like!
Yes! Thank you for teaching me 3 years ago that I did not need to set my eye primer with a light shade. It was life changing :)

Yes! Yes! Yes! I always eye roll at the girls in their 20s saying it doesn’t crease or sink into their lines. I love your channel and Heather’s because of the age, skin type, climate, and style similarities. Plus you both have such honest reviews. If I see something new I have to check to see what Angie and Heather think first 😂

When things get really hyped up now, I feel like I wait and see what the general public says about. I fell for it too many times.

I’ve heard a few Youtubers talk about products that they want to try but they wouldn’t purchase and immediately turn around and ask the brand to send them it as PR. I’m always shocked after that when they actually send it to them. I understand the point of PR, but if you’re not willing to spend your own money on something then don’t turn around and tell us it’s worth spending our money on. It just makes me look at them differently.**
Sometimes I just watch people because I love their personalities. And then i forget that we don’t have the same preferences and then I buy everything they love oooopppssss 😂

first_page_comments_list.comment: I think probably the biggest red-flag phrase has got to be "This has changed my life!"  Like, unless that foundation is clearing your debt or getting you free childcare, it's not changing your life.

I think “makeup education” (for lack of a better term) plays a huge role in this. I had this one palette that was my ride or die palette, and it cost maybe $10 on sale. I used this thing non stop. I thought it was the best palette on the planet. Best formula, best everything. Then it broke and died, so I went searching for another one. During that quest, I found other brands and other palettes, and realized what I had been using was utter garbage. But I didn’t know that at the time! I was an ignorant happy clam with this horrific palette! I wonder if I was better off back then…it was much cheaper….but now I know what works for me and what doesn’t, and why, ect. So maybe it’s more of “makeup exposure “ than education, but I would have defended that garbage palette in comments (had I watched YouTube prior to the lock down) in videos with zero hesitation! My makeup knowledge was basically nonexistent.  I believe this to be part of the makeup view disconnect on many occasions.

Sorry for the long comment in advance!! I strongly dislike how she handled Lashgate but what pisses me off about her the most is she literally outed Cody’s ex for having a drug addiction which in turn sent her huge fanbase after this poor girl. I am a recovering addict with 4 years of sobriety so to me, what she did to that girl is so disgusting. She can talk about Cody all she wants in that regard if he allows it, that’s his business. I am always open about my addiction as well but I still wouldn’t want anyone talking about that online without my permission, especially someone so huge, and Mikayla clearly didn’t have it. I was disappointed to see that she told the entire internet about those struggles, especially when it seems like this girl was already having a hard time, but sending that many people to hate on her? It’s just cruel.

I could never support her anyway because I met someone who was personally bullied by her when they were in school. She cried when she told me how much it hurts her to see her bully all over social media. Its just sad to see how Mikayla acts. I would’ve loved to support a fellow New England girl who is making it in the beauty community, but she isn’t honest and clearly doesn’t care that she intentionally deceived her own fanbase. It could’ve already been over by now if she just said she put a lash on at the end and forgot to add a caption or tell everyone about it in the last clip! Like seriously! Oh well, it’s not like we can even see how anything looks on her skin with all the filters.

Anyway, I’m just tired of fake people. Dealt with enough in my life already so the last thing I want is to be wasting time on superficial influencers who value a dollar over the trust of their audience. Glad we have some of the good ones left, like you! Bc you don’t use these crazy filters, you are outspoken and upfront about any sponsorships, we know you don’t take just anything that comes your way either and you actually like the products you promote. So thank you for always being yourself and real with us.

I value and trust your opinions on makeup, even though there are things I won’t get because of personal preference or our different skin types. (for example, orange is the worst color on me but it looks perfect on you) for me I try to be thoughtful about what to buy and I would never be able to consider only one person’s review as the deciding factor of making that choice. You made some really good points. Glad you’re not afraid to speak out.
For foundation, i look at how long they think a "full day" is! An 8 hour wear test is kinda useless to me. I appreciate that you aim for 10-12 hours when you can!

You mentioned how different shadows (neutrals, blues, neons, etc) have different techniques and things you can and can't do with them. I would be interested in an overview video of different techniques you use for different kinds of shadows

My biggest red flag is when an influencer does a first impression on a bunch of products, finds one that they consider “life changing” and then never uses it again or maybe talks about it once six months after the the first impression video. A good review of a product for me is when the influencer tries a product as a first impression, says they really like it, and continues to use it in future videos (as an example). That lets me know that they truly enjoy the product. Now, does that make me want to buy the product? Not always, because I watch a bunch of different people with a variety of different skin types. I have dry skin and am prone to hormonal acne.

They found a Maybelline powder video that Makayla did recently where she never showed the actual application and acted as if it was the second coming of Jesus as she hid the sponsored statement or added it later. She lies about the false lashes and then didn't respond about it at all and she hid the sponsored statement and doubled down on her lies and made a joke out of her actions in subsequent videos. She has used filters too.  She has yet to apologize and she shouldn't be given the benefit of the doubt at all. That ship sailed.

The lash gate situation isn’t about her doing it. It is about the lack of accountability. A little mea culpa would go such a long way to fixing the situation.  This is a teachable moment for her, but she doesn’t seem to be learning.

My red flag is when they like EVERYTHING.   Every product can’t be life changing. Not all products are going to work for you but some people react to anything new like its the greatest thing they’ve ever tried. And the over the top excitement that doesn’t feel genuine.

A “red flag” that I learned yeeeears ago (been watching beauty videos since the beginning of time, lol), is when a beauty reviewer says “it’s the PEEEERRRRFECT nude lipstick!”. That doesn’t happen as much today, because people have become more educated on different skin tones and undertones, but 10-15 years ago, beauty enthusiasts on YouTube would recommend a nude lipstick shade as “universal”, calling it absolutely perfect for anyone, when obviously a nude depends on each individual’s unique coloring.

There are only a couple I trust now. We aren't stupid, when you watch long enough, you can see their tells and know when they are not into a product. Or when they are just don't something to help a brand. It's disgusting. I've really backed off the number of videos I watch because I just don't trust hardly anyone anymore. And yes, a first impression is a first impression, not a "review with swatches". Even if you do 3 looks in the video, if you're wiping them of to do another you aren't reviewing, you don't know how long it will wear, if it will cease, fade, etc. The smaller creators I used to love have gotten bigger and we're back to codes and links being pushed just like the bigger creators. I'm so disgusted with this community yet again. I watch you and like 3 other religiously, and then some others here and there, but I don't believe anything they say. The other thing that aggravates me is when their community tab has links to all releases, even if they haven't tried them or like them. It's all about the money for their links. If i wanted one long a$$ commercial, I'd watch TV. There's my rant for the day lol. 🤪

I’ll be 51 in 17 days and I personally can not thank you enough for this video! I don’t trust many, and honestly some creators are just amusing to me (not in a good way). I do trust you and that’s why I’m always here for it!
The problem with mikayla it’s that she didn’t even adress the problem, she is mocking the situation, and that it’s unacceptable. And the thing that other people have done worst it’s not an excuse.

The issue with Makayla is that she clearly put in the comments she was NOT wearing lashes as she was questioned. That’s just sad and awful.

It’s nice to find creators over 45 so thanks for the tag!
My biggest pet peeve’s is when a influencer call every other product a holy grail. 9 times out of 10 you’ll never see them use it again, and the misuse of the phrase life hanging. 💕
Yesssss I totally agree ❤sometimes hearing what people don’t like can be just as helpful as hearing what people do like!
Yes! Thank you for teaching me 3 years ago that I did not need to set my eye primer with a light shade. It was life changing :)

Yes! Yes! Yes! I always eye roll at the girls in their 20s saying it doesn’t crease or sink into their lines. I love your channel and Heather’s because of the age, skin type, climate, and style similarities. Plus you both have such honest reviews. If I see something new I have to check to see what Angie and Heather think first 😂

When things get really hyped up now, I feel like I wait and see what the general public says about. I fell for it too many times.

I’ve heard a few Youtubers talk about products that they want to try but they wouldn’t purchase and immediately turn around and ask the brand to send them it as PR. I’m always shocked after that when they actually send it to them. I understand the point of PR, but if you’re not willing to spend your own money on something then don’t turn around and tell us it’s worth spending our money on. It just makes me look at them differently.**
Sometimes I just watch people because I love their personalities. And then i forget that we don’t have the same preferences and then I buy everything they love oooopppssss 😂

first_page_comments_list.comment: I think probably the biggest red-flag phrase has got to be "This has changed my life!"  Like, unless that foundation is clearing your debt or getting you free childcare, it's not changing your life.

I think “makeup education” (for lack of a better term) plays a huge role in this. I had this one palette that was my ride or die palette, and it cost maybe $10 on sale. I used this thing non stop. I thought it was the best palette on the planet. Best formula, best everything. Then it broke and died, so I went searching for another one. During that quest, I found other brands and other palettes, and realized what I had been using was utter garbage. But I didn’t know that at the time! I was an ignorant happy clam with this horrific palette! I wonder if I was better off back then…it was much cheaper….but now I know what works for me and what doesn’t, and why, ect. So maybe it’s more of “makeup exposure “ than education, but I would have defended that garbage palette in comments (had I watched YouTube prior to the lock down) in videos with zero hesitation! My makeup knowledge was basically nonexistent.  I believe this to be part of the makeup view disconnect on many occasions.

Sorry for the long comment in advance!! I strongly dislike how she handled Lashgate but what pisses me off about her the most is she literally outed Cody’s ex for having a drug addiction which in turn sent her huge fanbase after this poor girl. I am a recovering addict with 4 years of sobriety so to me, what she did to that girl is so disgusting. She can talk about Cody all she wants in that regard if he allows it, that’s his business. I am always open about my addiction as well but I still wouldn’t want anyone talking about that online without my permission, especially someone so huge, and Mikayla clearly didn’t have it. I was disappointed to see that she told the entire internet about those struggles, especially when it seems like this girl was already having a hard time, but sending that many people to hate on her? It’s just cruel.

I could never support her anyway because I met someone who was personally bullied by her when they were in school. She cried when she told me how much it hurts her to see her bully all over social media. Its just sad to see how Mikayla acts. I would’ve loved to support a fellow New England girl who is making it in the beauty community, but she isn’t honest and clearly doesn’t care that she intentionally deceived her own fanbase. It could’ve already been over by now if she just said she put a lash on at the end and forgot to add a caption or tell everyone about it in the last clip! Like seriously! Oh well, it’s not like we can even see how anything looks on her skin with all the filters.

Anyway, I’m just tired of fake people. Dealt with enough in my life already so the last thing I want is to be wasting time on superficial influencers who value a dollar over the trust of their audience. Glad we have some of the good ones left, like you! Bc you don’t use these crazy filters, you are outspoken and upfront about any sponsorships, we know you don’t take just anything that comes your way either and you actually like the products you promote. So thank you for always being yourself and real with us.

I value and trust your opinions on makeup, even though there are things I won’t get because of personal preference or our different skin types. (for example, orange is the worst color on me but it looks perfect on you) for me I try to be thoughtful about what to buy and I would never be able to consider only one person’s review as the deciding factor of making that choice. You made some really good points. Glad you’re not afraid to speak out.
For foundation, i look at how long they think a "full day" is! An 8 hour wear test is kinda useless to me. I appreciate that you aim for 10-12 hours when you can!

You mentioned how different shadows (neutrals, blues, neons, etc) have different techniques and things you can and can't do with them. I would be interested in an overview video of different techniques you use for different kinds of shadows

My biggest red flag is when an influencer does a first impression on a bunch of products, finds one that they consider “life changing” and then never uses it again or maybe talks about it once six months after the the first impression video. A good review of a product for me is when the influencer tries a product as a first impression, says they really like it, and continues to use it in future videos (as an example). That lets me know that they truly enjoy the product. Now, does that make me want to buy the product? Not always, because I watch a bunch of different people with a variety of different skin types. I have dry skin and am prone to hormonal acne.

They found a Maybelline powder video that Makayla did recently where she never showed the actual application and acted as if it was the second coming of Jesus as she hid the sponsored statement or added it later. She lies about the false lashes and then didn't respond about it at all and she hid the sponsored statement and doubled down on her lies and made a joke out of her actions in subsequent videos. She has used filters too.  She has yet to apologize and she shouldn't be given the benefit of the doubt at all. That ship sailed.

The lash gate situation isn’t about her doing it. It is about the lack of accountability. A little mea culpa would go such a long way to fixing the situation.  This is a teachable moment for her, but she doesn’t seem to be learning.

My red flag is when they like EVERYTHING.   Every product can’t be life changing. Not all products are going to work for you but some people react to anything new like its the greatest thing they’ve ever tried. And the over the top excitement that doesn’t feel genuine.

A “red flag” that I learned yeeeears ago (been watching beauty videos since the beginning of time, lol), is when a beauty reviewer says “it’s the PEEEERRRRFECT nude lipstick!”. That doesn’t happen as much today, because people have become more educated on different skin tones and undertones, but 10-15 years ago, beauty enthusiasts on YouTube would recommend a nude lipstick shade as “universal”, calling it absolutely perfect for anyone, when obviously a nude depends on each individual’s unique coloring.

There are only a couple I trust now. We aren't stupid, when you watch long enough, you can see their tells and know when they are not into a product. Or when they are just don't something to help a brand. It's disgusting. I've really backed off the number of videos I watch because I just don't trust hardly anyone anymore. And yes, a first impression is a first impression, not a "review with swatches". Even if you do 3 looks in the video, if you're wiping them of to do another you aren't reviewing, you don't know how long it will wear, if it will cease, fade, etc. The smaller creators I used to love have gotten bigger and we're back to codes and links being pushed just like the bigger creators. I'm so disgusted with this community yet again. I watch you and like 3 other religiously, and then some others here and there, but I don't believe anything they say. The other thing that aggravates me is when their community tab has links to all releases, even if they haven't tried them or like them. It's all about the money for their links. If i wanted one long a$$ commercial, I'd watch TV. There's my rant for the day lol. 🤪

I’ll be 51 in 17 days and I personally can not thank you enough for this video! I don’t trust many, and honestly some creators are just amusing to me (not in a good way). I do trust you and that’s why I’m always here for it!
The problem with mikayla it’s that she didn’t even adress the problem, she is mocking the situation, and that it’s unacceptable. And the thing that other people have done worst it’s not an excuse.

The issue with Makayla is that she clearly put in the comments she was NOT wearing lashes as she was questioned. That’s just sad and awful.

It’s nice to find creators over 45 so thanks for the tag!
My biggest pet peeve’s is when a influencer call every other product a holy grail. 9 times out of 10 you’ll never see them use it again, and the misuse of the phrase life hanging. 💕
Yesssss I totally agree ❤sometimes hearing what people don’t like can be just as helpful as hearing what people do like!
Yes! Thank you for teaching me 3 years ago that I did not need to set my eye primer with a light shade. It was life changing :)

Yes! Yes! Yes! I always eye roll at the girls in their 20s saying it doesn’t crease or sink into their lines. I love your channel and Heather’s because of the age, skin type, climate, and style similarities. Plus you both have such honest reviews. If I see something new I have to check to see what Angie and Heather think first 😂

When things get really hyped up now, I feel like I wait and see what the general public says about. I fell for it too many times.

I’ve heard a few Youtubers talk about products that they want to try but they wouldn’t purchase and immediately turn around and ask the brand to send them it as PR. I’m always shocked after that when they actually send it to them. I understand the point of PR, but if you’re not willing to spend your own money on something then don’t turn around and tell us it’s worth spending our money on. first_page_comments_list.comment: I think probably the biggest red-flag phrase has got to be "This has changed my life!"  Like, unless that foundation is clearing your debt or getting you free childcare, it's not changing your life.

I think “makeup education” (for lack of a better term) plays a huge role in this. I had this one palette that was my ride or die palette, and it cost maybe $10 on sale. I used this thing non stop. I thought it was the best palette on the planet. Best formula, best everything. Then it broke and died, so I went searching for another one. During that quest, I found other brands and other palettes, and realized what I had been using was utter garbage. But I didn’t know that at the time! I was an ignorant happy clam with this horrific palette! I wonder if I was better off back then…it was much cheaper….but now I know what works for me and what doesn’t, and why, ect. So maybe it’s more of “makeup exposure “ than education, but I would have defended that garbage palette in comments (had I watched YouTube prior to the lock down) in videos with zero hesitation! My makeup knowledge was basically nonexistent.  I believe this to be part of the makeup view disconnect on many occasions.

Sorry for the long comment in advance!! I strongly dislike how she handled Lashgate but what pisses me off about her the most is she literally outed Cody’s ex for having a drug addiction which in turn sent her huge fanbase after this poor girl. I am a recovering addict with 4 years of sobriety so to me, what she did to that girl is so disgusting. She can talk about Cody all she wants in that regard if he allows it, that’s his business. I am always open about my addiction as well but I still wouldn’t want anyone talking about that online without my permission, especially someone so huge, and Mikayla clearly didn’t have it. I was disappointed to see that she told the entire internet about those struggles, especially when it seems like this girl was already having a hard time, but sending that many people to hate on her? It’s just cruel.

I could never support her anyway because I met someone who was personally bullied by her when they were in school. She cried when she told me how much it hurts her to see her bully all over social media. Its just sad to see how Mikayla acts. I would’ve loved to support a fellow New England girl who is making it in the beauty community, but she isn’t honest and clearly doesn’t care that she intentionally deceived her own fanbase. It could’ve already been over by now if she just said she put a lash on at the end and forgot to add a caption or tell everyone about it in the last clip! Like seriously! Oh well, it’s not like we can even see how anything looks on her skin with all the filters.

Anyway, I’m just tired of fake people. Dealt with enough in my life already so the last thing I want is to be wasting time on superficial influencers who value a dollar over the trust of their audience. Glad we have some of the good ones left, like you! Bc you don’t use these crazy filters, you are outspoken and upfront about any sponsorships, we know you don’t take just anything that comes your way either and you actually like the products you promote. So thank you for always being yourself and real with us.

I value and trust your opinions on makeup, even though there are things I won’t get because of personal preference or our different skin types. (for example, orange is the worst color on me but it looks perfect on you) for me I try to be thoughtful about what to buy and I would never be able to consider only one person’s review as the deciding factor of making that choice. You made some really good points. Glad you’re not afraid to speak out.
For foundation, i look at how long they think a "full day" is! An 8 hour wear test is kinda useless to me. I appreciate that you aim for 10-12 hours when you can!

You mentioned how different shadows (neutrals, blues, neons, etc) have different techniques and things you can and can't do with them. I would be interested in an overview video of different techniques you use for different kinds of shadows

My biggest red flag is when an influencer does a first impression on a bunch of products, finds one that they consider “life changing” and then never uses it again or maybe talks about it once six months after the the first impression video. A good review of a product for me is when the influencer tries a product as a first impression, says they really like it, and continues to use it in future videos (as an example). That lets me know that they truly enjoy the product. Now, does that make me want to buy the product? Not always, because I watch a bunch of different people with a variety of different skin types. I have dry skin and am prone to hormonal acne.

They found a Maybelline powder video that Makayla did recently where she never showed the actual application and acted as if it was the second coming of Jesus as she hid the sponsored statement or added it later. She lies about the false lashes and then didn't respond about it at all and she hid the sponsored statement and doubled down on her lies and made a joke out of her actions in subsequent videos. She has used filters too.  She has yet to apologize and she shouldn't be given the benefit of the doubt at all. That ship sailed.

The lash gate situation isn’t about her doing it. It is about the lack of accountability. A little mea culpa would go such a long way to fixing the situation.  This is a teachable moment for her, but she doesn’t seem to be learning.

My red flag is when they like EVERYTHING.   Every product can’t be life changing. Not all products are going to work for you but some people react to anything new like its the greatest thing they’ve ever tried. And the over the top excitement that doesn’t feel genuine.

A “red flag” that I learned yeeeears ago (been watching beauty videos since the beginning of time, lol), is when a beauty reviewer says “it’s the PEEEERRRRFECT nude lipstick!”. That doesn’t happen as much today, because people have become more educated on different skin tones and undertones, but 10-15 years ago, beauty enthusiasts on YouTube would recommend a nude lipstick shade as “universal”, calling it absolutely perfect for anyone, when obviously a nude depends on each individual’s unique coloring.

There are only a couple I trust now. We aren't stupid, when you watch long enough, you can see their tells and know when they are not into a product. Or when they are just don't something to help a brand. It's disgusting. I've really backed off the number of videos I watch because I just don't trust hardly anyone anymore. And yes, a first impression is a first impression, not a "review with swatches". Even if you do 3 looks in the video, if you're wiping them of to do another you aren't reviewing, you don't know how long it will wear, if it will cease, fade, etc. The smaller creators I used to love have gotten bigger and we're back to codes and links being pushed just like the bigger creators. I'm so disgusted with this community yet again. I watch you and like 3 other religiously, and then some others here and there, but I don't believe anything they say. The other thing that aggravates me is when their community tab has links to all releases, even if they haven't tried them or like them. It's all about the money for their links. If i wanted one long a$$ commercial, I'd watch TV. There's my rant for the day lol. 🤪

I’ll be 51 in 17 days and I personally can not thank you enough for this video! I don’t trust many, and honestly some creators are just amusing to me (not in a good way). I do trust you and that’s why I’m always here for it!
The problem with mikayla it’s that she didn’t even adress the problem, she is mocking the situation, and that it’s unacceptable. And the thing that other people have done worst it’s not an excuse.

The issue with Makayla is that she clearly put in the comments she was NOT wearing lashes as she was questioned. That’s just sad and awful.

It’s nice to find creators over 45 so thanks for the tag!
My biggest pet peeve’s is when a influencer call every other product a holy grail. 9 times out of 10 you’ll never see them use it again, and the misuse of the phrase life hanging. 💕
Yesssss I totally agree ❤sometimes hearing what people don’t like can be just as helpful as hearing what people do like!
Yes! Thank you for teaching me 3 years ago that I did not need to set my eye primer with a light shade. It was life changing :)

Yes! Yes! Yes! I always eye roll at the girls in their 20s saying it doesn’t crease or sink into their lines. I love your channel and Heather’s because of the age, skin type, climate, and style similarities. Plus you both have such honest reviews. If I see something new I have to check to see what Angie and Heather think first 😂

When things get really hyped up now, I feel like I wait and see what the general public says about. I fell for it too many times.

I’ve heard a few Youtubers talk about products that they want to try but they wouldn’t purchase and immediately turn around and ask the brand to send them it as PR. I’m always shocked after that when they actually send it to them. I understand the point of PR, but if you’re not willing to spend your own money on something then don’t turn around and tell us it’s worth spending our money on. It just makes me look at them differently.**
Sometimes I just watch people because I love their personalities. And then i forget that we don’t have the same preferences and then I buy everything they love oooopppssss 😂

first_page_comments_list.comment: I think probably the biggest red-flag phrase has got to be "This has changed my life!"  Like, unless that foundation is clearing your debt or getting you free childcare, it's not changing your life.

I think “makeup education” (for lack of a better term) plays a huge role in this. I had this one palette that was my ride or die palette, and it cost maybe $10 on sale. I used this thing non stop. I thought it was the best palette on the planet. Best formula, best everything. Then it broke and died, so I went searching for another one. During that quest, I found other brands and other palettes, and realized what I had been using was utter garbage. But I didn’t know that at the time! I was an ignorant happy clam with this horrific palette! I wonder if I was better off back then…it was much cheaper….but now I know what works for me and what doesn’t, and why, ect. So maybe it’s more of “makeup exposure “ than education, but I would have defended that garbage palette in comments (had I watched YouTube prior to the lock down) in videos with zero hesitation! My makeup knowledge was basically nonexistent.  I believe this to be part of the makeup view disconnect on many occasions.

Sorry for the long comment in advance!! I strongly dislike how she handled Lashgate but what pisses me off about her the most is she literally outed Cody’s ex for having a drug addiction which in turn sent her huge fanbase after this poor girl. I am a recovering addict with 4 years of sobriety so to me, what she did to that girl is so disgusting. She can talk about Cody all she wants in that regard if he allows it, that’s his business. I am always open about my addiction as well but I still wouldn’t want anyone talking about that online without my permission, especially someone so huge, and Mikayla clearly didn’t have it. I was disappointed to see that she told the entire internet about those struggles, especially when it seems like this girl was already having a hard time, but sending that many people to hate on her? It’s just cruel.

I could never support her anyway because I met someone who was personally bullied by her when they were in school. She cried when she told me how much it hurts her to see her bully all over social media. Its just sad to see how Mikayla acts. I would’ve loved to support a fellow New England girl who is making it in the beauty community, but she isn’t honest and clearly doesn’t care that she intentionally deceived her own fanbase. It could’ve already been over by now if she just said she put a lash on at the end and forgot to add a caption or tell everyone about it in the last clip! Like seriously! Oh well, it’s not like we can even see how anything looks on her skin with all the filters.

Anyway, I’m just tired of fake people. Dealt with enough in my life already so the last thing I want is to be wasting time on superficial influencers who value a dollar over the trust of their audience. Glad we have some of the good ones left, like you! Bc you don’t use these crazy filters, you are outspoken and upfront about any sponsorships, we know you don’t take just anything that comes your way either and you actually like the products you promote. So thank you for always being yourself and real with us.

I value and trust your opinions on makeup, even though there are things I won’t get because of personal preference or our different skin types. (for example, orange is the worst color on me but it looks perfect on you) for me I try to be thoughtful about what to buy and I would never be able to consider only one person’s review as the deciding factor of making that choice. You made some really good points. Glad you’re not afraid to speak out.
For foundation, i look at how long they think a "full day" is! An 8 hour wear test is kinda useless to me. I appreciate that you aim for 10-12 hours when you can!

You mentioned how different shadows (neutrals, blues, neons, etc) have different techniques and things you can and can't do with them. I would be interested in an overview video of different techniques you use for different kinds of shadows

My biggest red flag is when an influencer does a first impression on a bunch of products, finds one that they consider “life changing” and then never uses it again or maybe talks about it once six months after the the first impression video. A good review of a product for me is when the influencer tries a product as a first impression, says they really like it, and continues to use it in future videos (as an example). That lets me know that they truly enjoy the product. Now, does that make me want to buy the product? Not always, because I watch a bunch of different people with a variety of different skin types. I have dry skin and am prone to hormonal acne.

They found a Maybelline powder video that Makayla did recently where she never showed the actual application and acted as if it was the second coming of Jesus as she hid the sponsored statement or added it later. She lies about the false lashes and then didn't respond about it at all and she hid the sponsored statement and doubled down on her lies and made a joke out of her actions in subsequent videos. She has used filters too.  She has yet to apologize and she shouldn't be given the benefit of the doubt at all. That ship sailed.

The lash gate situation isn’t about her doing it. It is about the lack of accountability. A little mea culpa would go such a long way to fixing the situation.  This is a teachable moment for her, but she doesn’t seem to be learning.

My red flag is when they like EVERYTHING.   Every product can’t be life changing. Not all products are going to work for you but some people react to anything new like its the greatest thing they’ve ever tried. And the over the top excitement that doesn’t feel genuine.

A “red flag” that I learned yeeeears ago (been watching beauty videos since the beginning of time, lol), is when a beauty reviewer says “it’s the PEEEERRRRFECT nude lipstick!”. That doesn’t happen as much today, because people have become more educated on different skin tones and undertones, but 10-15 years ago, beauty enthusiasts on YouTube would recommend a nude lipstick shade as “universal”, calling it absolutely perfect for anyone, when obviously a nude depends on each individual’s unique coloring.

There are only a couple I trust now. We aren't stupid, when you watch long enough, you can see their tells and know when they are not into a product. Or when they are just don't something to help a brand. It's disgusting. I've really backed off the number of videos I watch because I just don't trust hardly anyone anymore. And yes, a first impression is a first impression, not a "review with swatches". Even if you do 3 looks in the video, if you're wiping them of to do another you aren't reviewing, you don't know how long it will wear, if it will cease, fade, etc. The smaller creators I used to love have gotten bigger and we're back to codes and links being pushed just like the bigger creators. I'm so disgusted with this community yet again. I watch you and like 3 other religiously, and then some others here and there, but I don't believe anything they say. The other thing that aggravates me is when their community tab has links to all releases, even if they haven't tried them or like them. It's all about the money for their links. If i wanted one long a$$ commercial, I'd watch TV. There's my rant for the day lol. 🤪

I’ll be 51 in 17 days and I personally can not thank you enough for this video! I don’t trust many, and honestly some creators are just amusing to me (not in a good way). I do trust you and that’s why I’m always here for it!
The problem with mikayla it’s that she didn’t even adress the problem, she is mocking the situation, and that it’s unacceptable. And the thing that other people have done worst it’s not an excuse.

The issue with Makayla is that she clearly put in the comments she was NOT wearing lashes as she was questioned. That’s just sad and awful.

It’s nice to find creators over 45 so thanks for the tag!
My biggest pet peeve’s is when a influencer call every other product a holy grail. 9 times out of 10 you’ll never see them use it again, and the misuse of the phrase life hanging. 💕
Yesssss I totally agree ❤sometimes hearing what people don’t like can be just as helpful as hearing what people do like!
Yes! Thank you for teaching me 3 years ago that I did not need to set my eye primer with a light shade. It was life changing :)

Yes! Yes! Yes! I always eye roll at the girls in their 20s saying it doesn’t crease or sink into their lines. I love your channel and Heather’s because of the age, skin type, climate, and style similarities. Plus you both have such honest reviews. If I see something new I have to check to see what Angie and Heather think first 😂

When things get really hyped up now, I feel like I wait and see what the general public says about. I fell for it too many times.

I’ve heard a few Youtubers talk about products that they want to try but they wouldn’t purchase and immediately turn around and ask the brand to send them it as PR. I’m always shocked after that when they actually send it to them. I understand the point of PR, but if you’re not willing to spend your own money on something then don’t turn around and tell us it’s worth spending our money on. It just makes me look at them differently.**
Sometimes I just watch people because I love their personalities. And then i forget that we don’t have the same preferences and then I buy everything they love oooopppssss 😂

first_page_comments_list.comment: I think probably the biggest red-flag phrase has got to be "This has changed my life!"  Like, unless that foundation is clearing your debt or getting you free childcare, it's not changing your life.

I think “makeup education” (for lack of a better term) plays a huge role in this. I had this one palette that was my ride or die palette, and it cost maybe $10 on sale. I used this thing non stop. I thought it was the best palette on the planet. Best formula, best everything. Then it broke and died, so I went searching for another one. During that quest, I found other brands and other palettes, and realized what I had been using was utter garbage. But I didn’t know that at the time! I was an ignorant happy clam with this horrific palette! I wonder if I was better off back then…it was much cheaper….but now I know what works for me and what doesn’t, and why, ect. So maybe it’s more of “makeup exposure “ than education, but I would have defended that garbage palette in comments (had I watched YouTube prior to the lock down) in videos with zero hesitation! My makeup knowledge was basically nonexistent.  I believe this to be part of the makeup view disconnect on many occasions.

Sorry for the long comment in advance!! I strongly dislike how she handled Lashgate but what pisses me off about her the most is she literally outed Cody’s ex for having a drug addiction which in turn sent her huge fanbase after this poor girl. I am a recovering addict with 4 years of sobriety so to me, what she did to that girl is so disgusting. She can talk about Cody all she wants in that regard if he allows it, that’s his business. I am always open about my addiction as well but I still wouldn’t want anyone talking about that online without my permission, especially someone so huge, and Mikayla clearly didn’t have it. I was disappointed to see that she told the entire internet about those struggles, especially when it seems like this girl was already having a hard time, but sending that many people to hate on her? It’s just cruel.

I could never support her anyway because I met someone who was personally bullied by her when they were in school. She cried when she told me how much it hurts her to see her bully all over social media. Its just sad to see how Mikayla acts. I would’ve loved to support a fellow New England girl who is making it in the beauty community, but she isn’t honest and clearly doesn’t care that she intentionally deceived her own fanbase. It could’ve already been over by now if she just said she put a lash on at the end and forgot to add a caption or tell everyone about it in the last clip! Like seriously! Oh well, it’s not like we can even see how anything looks on her skin with all the filters.

Anyway, I’m just tired of fake people. Dealt with enough in my life already so the last thing I want is to be wasting time on superficial influencers who value a dollar over the trust of their audience. Glad we have some of the good ones left, like you! Bc you don’t use these crazy filters, you are outspoken and upfront about any sponsorships, we know you don’t take just anything that comes your way either and you actually like the products you promote. So thank you for always being yourself and real with us.

I value and trust your opinions on makeup, even though there are things I won’t get because of personal preference or our different skin types. (for example, orange is the worst color on me but it looks perfect on you) for me I try to be thoughtful about what to buy and I would never be able to consider only one person’s review as the deciding factor of making that choice. You made some really good points. Glad you’re not afraid to speak out.
For foundation, i look at how long they think a "full day" is! An 8 hour wear test is kinda useless to me. I appreciate that you aim for 10-12 hours when you can!

You mentioned how different shadows (neutrals, blues, neons, etc) have different techniques and things you can and can't do with them. I would be interested in an overview video of different techniques you use for different kinds of shadows

My biggest red flag is when an influencer does a first impression on a bunch of products, finds one that they consider “life changing” and then never uses it again or maybe talks about it once six months after the the first impression video. A good review of a product for me is when the influencer tries a product as a first impression, says they really like it, and continues to use it in future videos (as an example). That lets me know that they truly enjoy the product. Now, does that make me want to buy the product? Not always, because I watch a bunch of different people with a variety of different skin types. I have dry skin and am prone to hormonal acne.

They found a Maybelline powder video that Makayla did recently where she never showed the actual application and acted as if it was the second coming of Jesus as she hid the sponsored statement or added it later. She lies about the false lashes and then didn't respond about it at all and she hid the sponsored statement and doubled down on her lies and made a joke out of her actions in subsequent videos. She has used filters too.  She has yet to apologize and she shouldn't be given the benefit of the doubt at all. That ship sailed.

The lash gate situation isn’t about her doing it. It is about the lack of accountability. A little mea culpa would go such a long way to fixing the situation.  This is a teachable moment for her, but she doesn’t seem to be learning.

My red flag is when they like EVERYTHING.   Every product can’t be life changing. Not all products are going to work for you but some people react to anything new like its the greatest thing they’ve ever tried. And the over the top excitement that doesn’t feel genuine.

A “red flag” that I learned yeeeears ago (been watching beauty videos since the beginning of time, lol), is when a beauty reviewer says “it’s the PEEEERRRRFECT nude lipstick!”. That doesn’t happen as much today, because people have become more educated on different skin tones and undertones, but 10-15 years ago, beauty enthusiasts on YouTube would recommend a nude lipstick shade as “universal”, calling it absolutely perfect for anyone, when obviously a nude depends on each individual’s unique coloring.

There are only a couple I trust now. We aren't stupid, when you watch long enough, you can see their tells and know when they are not into a product. Or when they are just don't something to help a brand. It's disgusting. I've really backed off the number of videos I watch because I just don't trust hardly anyone anymore. And yes, a first impression is a first impression, not a "review with swatches". Even if you do 3 looks in the video, if you're wiping them of to do another you aren't reviewing, you don't know how long it will wear, if it will cease, fade, etc. The smaller creators I used to love have gotten bigger and we're back to codes and links being pushed just like the bigger creators. I'm so disgusted with this community yet again. I watch you and like 3 other religiously, and then some others here and there, but I don't believe anything they say. The other thing that aggravates me is when their community tab has links to all releases, even if they haven't tried them or like them. It's all about the money for their links. If i wanted one long a$$ commercial, I'd watch TV. There's my rant for the day lol. 🤪

I’ll be 51 in 17 days and I personally can not thank you enough for this video! I don’t trust many, and honestly some creators are just amusing to me (not in a good way). I do trust you and that’s why I’m always here for it!
The problem with mikayla it’s that she didn’t even adress the problem, she is mocking the situation, and that it’s unacceptable. And the thing that other people have done worst it’s not an excuse.

The issue with Makayla is that she clearly put in the comments she was NOT wearing lashes as she was questioned. That’s just sad and awful.

It’s nice to find creators over 45 so thanks for the tag!
My biggest pet peeve’s is when a influencer call every other product a holy grail. 9 times out of 10 you’ll never see them use it again, and the misuse of the phrase life hanging. 💕
Yesssss I totally agree ❤sometimes hearing what people don’t like can be just as helpful as hearing what people do like!
Yes! Thank you for teaching me 3 years ago that I did not need to set my eye primer with a light shade. It was life changing :)

Yes! Yes! Yes! I always eye roll at the girls in their 20s saying it doesn’t crease or sink into their lines. I love your channel and Heather’s because of the age, skin type, climate, and style similarities. Plus you both have such honest reviews. If I see something new I have to check to see what Angie and Heather think first 😂

When things get really hyped up now, I feel like I wait and see what the general public says about. I fell for it too many times.

I’ve heard a few Youtubers talk about products that they want to try but they wouldn’t purchase and immediately turn around and ask the brand to send them it as PR. I’m always shocked after that when they actually send it to them. I understand the point of PR, but if you’re not willing to spend your own money on something then don’t turn around and tell us it’s worth spending our money on. It just makes me look at them differently.**
Sometimes I just watch people because I love their personalities. And then i forget that we don’t have the same preferences and then I buy everything they love oooopppssss 😂
